  <span id="freeText9010334410270917247" style="display:none">This is an odd little book when compared to Ballard's other work. In this region of the country it is kind of a hard title to find, and both times that I have seen it in used stores it has been priced for collectors (for me that means over $12...yeah, i'm a cheapskate...). It is also very short, clocking in at just over a hundred pages.<br /><br />For those who are unfamiliar with Ballard, he had a fascination with what he called invisible literature. This is best described as documents written for a specific purpose other than as art and can include such things as medical journals, the Warren Commission report, technical writing, etc. He would often weave this sort of thing into his fiction, and this is one of the reasons that his prose comes across as somewhat clinically detached. This trait seems a bit offputting to some readers but I love it.<br /><br />'Running Wild' seems to be an experiment in the near total suppression of Ballard's own authorial voice. The entire book is written as a forensic diary of a police psychiatrist. Interesting experiment, but I think that this is the precise reason that I did not go all blubbery fanboy for this particular work. When Ballard combines pieces of reworked invisible literature to his own prose the end result zings like a high-tension power line. When Dr. Richard Greville does all of the talking, however, it...uh...sounds like something that was written by a police psychiatrist. <br /><br />This book delves into such things as modern surveillence society and the simmering ugliness that is boiling just under the surface of happy, well-adjusted suburbia, two themes that seem to be among Ballard's favorites throughout his later work. It was good to see them dissected from yet another perspective. There is a "surprise twist" in this book, but the possibility of it occurred to me only a few pages in. As 'Running Wild' was written in 1988, I believe that this was more a function of our world continually moving closer to conforming to Ballard's forecasts rather than my literary sleuthing abilities. I find this idea both exciting and scary in equal measure.<br /><br />While this is not one of my favorite Ballard titles, I still think that 'Running Wild' would be a good jumping-on point for anyone who has never read any of his work. It gives the reader a good idea of what Ballard was all about in his later work, but it is not as emotionally jarring as other titles.<br /></span>
